  abstract = {Ungulates in and climates use a variety of mechanisms to cope with\$$\backslash$backslash\$nenvironmental conditions that can result in heat stress and dehydration.\$$\backslash$backslash\$nUse of shade during midday is common among desert ungulates of the\$$\backslash$backslash\$nsouthwestern United States. Desert bighorn sheep (Ovis canadensis\$$\backslash$backslash\$nmexicana) use both vegetation and caves as sources of thermal cover. We\$$\backslash$backslash\$nassessed potential thermoregulatory advantages of the use of vegetation\$$\backslash$backslash\$nand caves by desert bighorn sheep on the Cabeza Prieta National Wildlife\$$\backslash$backslash\$nRefuge, Arizona. Midday ambient temperatures in caves were an average of\$$\backslash$backslash\$n6.9 degrees C (SE = 0.344) lower than control sites; ambient temperature\$$\backslash$backslash\$nunder tree canopies was an average of 3.3 degrees C (SE = 0.950) below\$$\backslash$backslash\$ncontrol sites. Caves provided higher quality shade than tree canopies;\$$\backslash$backslash\$nmidday temperature in caves was an average of 3.4 degrees C (SE = 1.06)\$$\backslash$backslash\$nlower than under tree canopies. Potential thermal benefits of both caves\$$\backslash$backslash\$nand tree canopies increased with increasing daily high temperature.\$$\backslash$backslash\$nBehavioral adaptations function in combination with physiological and\$$\backslash$backslash\$nmorphological mechanisms and are of critical importance for the\$$\backslash$backslash\$nmaintenance of temperature and water balance. Short-term physiological\$$\backslash$backslash\$nand ecological performance is influenced by habitat selection and use of\$$\backslash$backslash\$nmicrohabitat; abiotic factors (e.g., ambient temperature) can ultimately\$$\backslash$backslash\$ninfluence animal fitness and the demography of animal populations. (c)\$$\backslash$backslash\$n2008 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.},
