  abstract = {[(1) This study compared the size of territories occupied by cock red grouse with certain features of their habitat, and with their population processes, aggression and survival, during a population fluctuation within one area in north-east Scotland from 1957 to 1962. (2) Territorial boundaries often went along moraine ridges or other prominent topographical features. The commonest shape was a rectangle longer than broad. A few small territories were square, triangular, or almost circular. (3) All moorland ground covered predominantly by heather was occupied by territorial grouse every year. Mean territory size was inversely correlated with spring population density. The extremes in individual territories were 0.2 and 13.2 ha in different years. The smallest territories were usually occupied by unmated cocks, and the largest territories were sometimes occupied by cocks with two hens which later nested inside the same territory. (4) In any one year, the territory size of individual cock grouse was correlated with an index of their aggression towards their territorial neighbours. During years of high population density (but not at extremely high density), it was also secondarily correlated with the visibility from the territory, those territories on flat open ground being bigger than those among hillocks. Some cocks had territories in two or more consecutive years in the same place, when the visibility did not change appreciably. In these cases, changes in territory size in the second year corresponded with changes in aggression. (5) The survival of cock grouse over winter and summer, and their chances of breeding were correlated with their territory size. The number of young reared per pair was not correlated with territory size. (6) When breeding success (number of young reared per old bird) was poor in 1959, the surviving young that subsequently got territories lived longer than other birds reared in 1957, 1958 and 1960 when breeding was better. (7) A fluctuation in the breeding stock from one spring to another was caused by changes in the size of territories taken in the previous autumn by each successive year-class of young cocks. These changes in mean territory size were correlated with breeding success in the previous summer, but there is no evidence yet that this is a causal relationship. (8) Young cocks (hatched that year) took much bigger territories than older cocks during the years of decline in 1958 and 1959, but smaller territories than old ones during the subsequent increase in 1960. Young cocks were more aggressive than old cocks during 1959, but less aggressive in 1960. This was because territorial cocks reared in 1959, a year of big decline in population, were more aggressive and survived better, whether as young or old birds, than territorial cocks reared in other years.]},
  number = {2},
  journal = {Journal of Animal Ecology},
  author = {Watson, Adam and Miller, G. R.},
  year = {1971},
  pages = {367-383}
}

